# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bcrypt-hashing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] The bcrypt function is the default password hash algorithm for OpenBSD, and was the default for some Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] There are implementations of bcrypt in C, C++, C#, Embarcadero Delphi, Elixir, Go, Java, JavaScript, Perl, PHP, Ruby, Python, Rust, V (Vlang), Zig and other languages.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] Blowfish is notable among block ciphers for its expensive key setup phase.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] It starts off with subkeys in a standard state, then uses this state to perform a block encryption using part of the key, and uses the result of that encryption (which is more accurate at hashing) to replace some of the subkeys.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] Then it uses this modified state to encrypt another part of the key, and uses the result to replace more of the subkeys.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] It proceeds in this fashion, using a progressively modified state to hash the key and replace bits of state, until all subkeys have been set.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] Provos and Mazières took advantage of this, and took it further.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] They developed a new key setup algorithm for Blowfish, dubbing the resulting cipher "Eksblowfish" ("expensive key schedule Blowfish").
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] The key setup begins with a modified form of the standard Blowfish key setup, in which both the salt and password are used to set all subkeys.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] There are then a number of rounds in which the standard Blowfish keying algorithm is applied, using alternatively the salt and the password as the key, each round starting with the subkey state from the previous round.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] In theory, this is no stronger than the standard Blowfish key schedule, but the number of rekeying rounds is configurable; this process can therefore be made arbitrarily slow, which helps deter brute-force attacks upon the hash or salt.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] The input to the bcrypt function is the password string (up to 72 bytes), a numeric cost, and a 16-byte (128-bit) salt value.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] The bcrypt function uses these inputs to compute a 24-byte (192-bit) hash.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] The base-64 encoding in bcrypt uses the table `./ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789`, which differs from RFC 4648 Base64 encoding.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] The original bcrypt specification defined a prefix of `$2$`.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] The original specification did not define how to handle non-ASCII characters, nor how to handle a null terminator.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] With this change, the version was changed to `$2a$`.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] In June 2011, a bug was discovered in **crypt_blowfish**, a PHP implementation of bcrypt.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] It was mis-handling characters with the 8th bit set.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] They suggested that system administrators update their existing password database, replacing `$2a$` with `$2x$`, to indicate that those hashes are bad (and need to use the old broken algorithm).
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] They also suggested the idea of having **crypt_blowfish** emit `$2y$` for hashes generated by the fixed algorithm.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] Nobody else, including Canonical and OpenBSD, adopted the idea of 2x/2y.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] This version marker change was limited to **crypt_blowfish**.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] A bug was discovered in the OpenBSD implementation of bcrypt.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] It was using an unsigned 8-bit value to hold the length of the password.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] For passwords longer than 255 bytes, instead of being truncated at 72 bytes the password would be truncated at the lesser of 72 or the length modulo 256.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] For example, a 260 byte password would be truncated at 4 bytes rather than truncated at 72 bytes.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] When OpenBSD fixed this issue, they changed the version to `$2b$`.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] The bcrypt function below encrypts the text *"OrpheanBeholderScryDoubt"* 64 times using Blowfish.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] InitialState works as in the original Blowfish algorithm, populating the P-array and S-box entries with the fractional part of $\pi$ in hexadecimal.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] Hence, `ExpandKey(*state*, *key*, 0)` is the same as regular Blowfish key schedule since all XORs with the all-zero salt value are ineffectual.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] `ExpandKey(*state*, *salt*, 0)` is similar, but uses the salt as a 128-bit key.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] Many implementations of bcrypt truncate the password to the first 72 bytes, following the OpenBSD implementation.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] The mathematical algorithm itself requires initialization with 18 32-bit subkeys (equivalent to 72 octets/bytes).
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] The original specification of bcrypt does not mandate any one particular method for mapping text-based passwords from userland into numeric values for the algorithm.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] Note that the quote above mentions passwords "up to 56 bytes" even though the algorithm itself makes use of a 72 byte initial value.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] Implementations have varied in their approach of converting passwords into initial numeric values, including sometimes reducing the strength of passwords containing non-ASCII characters.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] Bcrypt is not a key derivation function (KDF).
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] For example, bcrypt cannot be used to derive a 512-bit key from a password.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] At the same time, algorithms like pbkdf2, scrypt, and argon2 *are* password-based key derivation functions - where the output is then used for the purpose of password hashing rather than just key derivation.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] Password hashing generally needs to complete < 1000 ms.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] In this scenario, bcrypt is stronger than pbkdf2, scrypt, and argon2.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] bcrypt has a maximum password length of 72 bytes.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] The password (which is UTF-8 encoded), is repeated until it is 72-bytes long.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] In the worst case a password is limited to 18 characters, when every character requires 4 bytes of UTF-8 encoding.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] In 2024 a single-sign-on service by Okta, Inc. announced a vulnerability due to the password being concatenated after the username and the pair hashed with bcrypt, resulting in the password being ignored for logins with a long-enough username.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] It is unclear why the canonical implementation deletes 8-bits from the resulting password hash.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] The encoding used by the canonical OpenBSD implementation uses the same Base64 alphabet as crypt, an atypical Base64 alphabet.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/bcrypt] As such, the encoding is not compatible with the more common RFC 4648 Base64 encoding.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] In cryptography, a **key derivation function** (**KDF**) is a cryptographic algorithm that derives one or more secret keys from a secret value such as a master key, a password, or a passphrase using a pseudorandom function (which typically uses a cryptographic hash function or block cipher).
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] KDFs can be used to stretch keys into longer keys or to obtain keys of a required format, such as converting a group element that is the result of a Diffie–Hellman key exchange into a symmetric key for use with AES.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] Keyed cryptographic hash functions are popular examples of pseudorandom functions used for key derivation.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] The first deliberately slow (key stretching) password-based key derivation function was called "crypt" (or "crypt(3)" after its man page), and was invented by Robert Morris in 1978.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] It would encrypt a constant (zero), using the first 8 characters of the user's password as the key, by performing 25 iterations of a modified DES encryption algorithm (in which a 12-bit number read from the real-time computer clock is used to perturb the calculations).
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] The resulting 64-bit number is encoded as 11 printable characters and then stored in the Unix password file.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] While it was a great advance at the time, increases in processor speeds since the PDP-11 era have made brute-force attacks against crypt feasible, and advances in storage have rendered the 12-bit salt inadequate.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] The crypt function's design also limits the user password to 8 characters, which limits the keyspace and makes strong passphrases impossible.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] Although high throughput is a desirable property in general-purpose hash functions, the opposite is true in password security applications in which defending against brute-force cracking is a primary concern.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] Various algorithms have been designed specifically for this purpose, including bcrypt, scrypt and, more recently, Lyra2 and Argon2 (the latter being the winner of the Password Hashing Competition).
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] The large-scale Ashley Madison data breach in which roughly 36 million passwords hashes were stolen by attackers illustrated the importance of algorithm selection in securing passwords.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) issued a new revision of their digital authentication guidelines, NIST SP 800-63B-3, stating that: "Verifiers SHALL store memorized secrets [i.e. passwords] in a form that is resistant to offline attacks.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] Memorized secrets SHALL be salted and hashed using a suitable one-way key derivation function.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] Key derivation functions take a password, a salt, and a cost factor as inputs then generate a password hash.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] Modern password-based key derivation functions, such as PBKDF2, are based on a recognized cryptographic hash, such as SHA-2, use more salt (at least 64 bits and chosen randomly) and a high iteration count.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] NIST recommends a minimum iteration count of 10,000.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] The original use for a KDF is key derivation, the generation of keys from secret passwords or passphrases.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] Key derivation functions are also used in applications to derive keys from secret passwords or passphrases, which typically do not have the desired properties to be used directly as cryptographic keys.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] In such applications, it is generally recommended that the key derivation function be made deliberately slow so as to frustrate brute-force attack or dictionary attack on the password or passphrase input value.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] Such use may be expressed as DK = KDF(key, salt, iterations), where DK is the derived key, KDF is the key derivation function, key is the original key or password, salt is a random number which acts as cryptographic salt, and iterations refers to the number of iterations of a sub-function.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] The derived key is used instead of the original key or password as the key to the system.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] The values of the salt and the number of iterations (if it is not fixed) are stored with the hashed password or sent as cleartext (unencrypted) with an encrypted message.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] The difficulty of a brute force attack is increased with the number of iterations.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] A practical limit on the iteration count is the unwillingness of users to tolerate a perceptible delay in logging into a computer or seeing a decrypted message.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] The use of salt prevents the attackers from precomputing a dictionary of derived keys.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] An alternative approach, called **key strengthening**, extends the key with a random salt, but then (unlike in key stretching) securely deletes the salt.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] This forces both the attacker and legitimate users to perform a brute-force search for the salt value.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] Although the paper that introduced key stretching referred to this earlier technique and intentionally chose a different name, the term "key strengthening" is now often (arguably incorrectly) used to refer to key stretching.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] Despite their original use for key derivation, KDFs are possibly better known for their use in **password hashing** (password verification by hash comparison), as used by the passwd file or shadow password file.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] Password hash functions should be relatively expensive to calculate in case of brute-force attacks, and KDFs are designed with this characteristic built in.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] The non-secret parameters are called "salt" in this context.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] In 2013 a Password Hashing Competition was announced to choose a new, standard algorithm for password hashing.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] On 20 July 2015 the competition ended and Argon2 was announced as the final winner.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/key-derivation-function] Four other algorithms received special recognition: Catena, Lyra2, Makwa and yescrypt.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Please verify that the NodeJS version you are using is a *stable* version; Unstable versions are currently not supported and issues created while using an unstable version will be closed.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] If you are on a stable version of NodeJS, please provide a sufficient code snippet or log files for installation issues.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] The code snippet does not require you to include confidential information.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] However, it must provide enough information so the problem can be replicable, or it may be closed without an explanation.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] `node-gyp` only works with stable/released versions of node.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Since the `bcrypt` module uses `node-gyp` to build and install, you'll need a stable version of node to use bcrypt.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] As should be the case with any security tool, anyone using this library should scrutinise it.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] If you find or suspect an issue with the code, please bring it to the maintainers' attention.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] We will spend some time ensuring that this library is as secure as possible.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Here is a list of BCrypt-related security issues/concerns that have come up over the years.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] This library supports `$2a$` and `$2b$` prefix bcrypt hashes.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] `$2x$` and `$2y$` hashes are specific to bcrypt implementation developed for John the Ripper.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] In theory, they should be compatible with `$2b$` prefix.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Compatibility with hashes generated by other languages is not 100% guaranteed due to difference in character encodings.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] However, it should not be an issue for most cases.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Hashes generated in earlier version of `bcrypt` remain 100% supported in `v2.x.x` and later versions.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] In most cases, the migration should be a bump in the `package.json`.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Hashes generated in `v2.x.x` using the defaults parameters will not work in earlier versions.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Only the current stable and supported LTS releases (Node 18+) are actively tested against.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Make sure you have the appropriate dependencies installed and configured for your platform.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] You can find installation instructions for the dependencies for some common platforms in this page.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Note that both techniques achieve the same end-result.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] bcrypt uses whatever `Promise` implementation is available in `global.Promise`.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] NodeJS has a native `Promise` implementation built in.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] However, this should work in any Promises/A+ compliant implementation.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Async methods that accept a callback, return a `Promise` when the callback is not specified if Promise support is available.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] As with async, both techniques achieve the same end-result.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] We recommend using async API if you use `bcrypt` on a server.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Bcrypt hashing is CPU intensive which will cause the sync APIs to block the event loop and prevent your application from servicing any inbound requests or events.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] The async version uses a thread pool which does not block the main event loop.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] A note about the cost: when you are hashing your data, the module will go through a series of rounds to give you a secure hash.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] The value you submit is not just the number of rounds the module will go through to hash your data.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] The module will use the value you enter and go through `2^rounds` hashing iterations.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Because it's come up multiple times in this project and other bcrypt projects, it needs to be said.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] The `bcrypt` library is not susceptible to timing attacks.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] However, the comparison function is *not* time safe (constant-time), as it may exit early when a mismatch is found.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Normally, this could enable a timing attack, but because it compares full bcrypt hash digests rather than raw passwords, and hashes are preimage-resistant, an attacker cannot gain any information about the stored hash.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] If you use the comparison function outside the bcrypt library, we cannot guarantee its security.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Keep this in mind when using the library.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] The characters that comprise the resultant hash are `./ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789$`.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/node-bcrypt-js] Unless stated elsewhere, file headers or otherwise, the license as stated in the LICENSE file.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] In cryptography, a **salt** is random data fed as an additional input to a one-way function that hashes data, a password or passphrase.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Salting helps defend against attacks that use precomputed tables (e.g. rainbow tables), by vastly growing the size of table needed for a successful attack.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] It also helps protect passwords that occur multiple times in a database, as a new salt is used for each password instance.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Additionally, salting does not place any burden on users.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Typically, a unique salt is randomly generated for each password.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] The salt and the password (or its version after key stretching) are concatenated and fed to a cryptographic hash function, and the output hash value is then stored with the salt in a database.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] The salt does not need to be encrypted, because knowing the salt would not help the attacker.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Salting is broadly used in cybersecurity, from Unix system credentials to Internet security.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Salts are related to cryptographic nonces.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Without a salt, identical passwords will map to identical hash values, which could make it easier for a hacker to guess the passwords from their hash value.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Instead, a salt is generated and appended to each password, which causes the resultant hash to output different values for the same original password.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] The salt and hash are then stored in the database.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] To later test if a password a user enters is correct, the same process can be performed on it (appending that user's salt to the password and calculating the resultant hash): if the result does not match the stored hash, it could not have been the correct password that was entered.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] In practice, a salt is usually generated using a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator (CSPRNG).
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] CSPRNGs are designed to produce unpredictable random numbers which can be alphanumeric.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] While generally discouraged due to lower security, some systems use timestamps or simple counters as a source of salt.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Sometimes, a salt may be generated by combining a random value with additional information, such as a timestamp or user-specific data, to ensure uniqueness across different systems or time periods.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Using the same salt for all passwords is dangerous because a precomputed table which simply accounts for the salt will render the salt useless.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Generation of precomputed tables for databases with unique salts for every password is not viable because of the computational cost of doing so.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] But, if a common salt is used for all the entries, creating such a table (that accounts for the salt) then becomes a viable and possibly successful attack.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Because salt re-use can cause users with the same password to have the same hash, cracking a single hash can result in other passwords being compromised too.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] If a salt is too short, an attacker may precompute a table of every possible salt appended to every likely password.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Using a long salt ensures such a table would be prohibitively large.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] 16 bytes (128 bits) or more is generally sufficient to provide a large enough space of possible values, minimizing the risk of collisions (i.e., two different passwords ending up with the same salt).
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] To understand the difference between cracking a single password and a set of them, consider a file with users and their hashed passwords.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Then an attacker could pick a string, call it `attempt[0]`, and then compute `hash(attempt[0])`.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] A user whose hash stored in the file is `hash(attempt[0])` may or may not have password `attempt[0]`.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] However, even if `attempt[0]` is *not* the user's actual password, it will be accepted as if it were, because the system can only check passwords by computing the hash of the password entered and comparing it to the hash stored in the file.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Thus, each match cracks a user password, and the chance of a match rises with the number of passwords in the file.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] In contrast, if salts are used, the attacker would have to compute `hash(attempt[0] || salt[a])`, compare against entry A, then `hash(attempt[0] || salt[b])`, compare against entry B, and so on.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] This prevents any one attempt from cracking multiple passwords, given that salt re-use is avoided.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Salts also combat the use of precomputed tables for cracking passwords.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Such a table might simply map common passwords to their hashes, or it might do something more complex, like store the start and end points of a set of precomputed hash chains.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] In either case, salting can defend against the use of precomputed tables by lengthening hashes and having them draw from larger character sets, making it less likely that the table covers the resulting hashes.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] In particular, a precomputed table would need to cover the string `[salt + hash]` rather than simply `[hash]`.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] The modern shadow password system, in which password hashes and other security data are stored in a non-public file, somewhat mitigates these concerns.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] However, they remain relevant in multi-server installations which use centralized password management systems to push passwords or password hashes to multiple systems.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Another (lesser) benefit of a salt is as follows: two users might choose the same string as their password.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Without a salt, this password would be stored as the same hash string in the password file.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] This would disclose the fact that the two accounts have the same password, allowing anyone who knows one of the account's passwords to access the other account.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] By salting the passwords with two random characters, even if two accounts use the same password, no one can discover this just by reading hashes.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Salting also makes it extremely difficult to determine if a person has used the same password for multiple systems.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Earlier versions of Unix used a password file `/etc/passwd` to store the hashes of salted passwords (passwords prefixed with two-character random salts).
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] In these older versions of Unix, the salt was also stored in the passwd file (as cleartext) together with the hash of the salted password.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] The password file was publicly readable for all users of the system.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] This was necessary so that user-privileged software tools could find user names and other information.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] The security of passwords is therefore protected only by the one-way functions (enciphering or hashing) used for the purpose.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Early Unix implementations limited passwords to eight characters and used a 12-bit salt, which allowed for 4,096 possible salt values.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] This was an appropriate balance for 1970s computational and storage costs.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] The shadow password system is used to limit access to hashes and salt.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] The salt is eight characters, the hash is 86 characters, and the password length is effectively unlimited, barring stack overflow errors.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] It is common for a web application to store in a database the hash value of a user's password.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Without a salt, a successful SQL injection attack may yield easily crackable passwords.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Because many users re-use passwords for multiple sites, the use of a salt is an important component of overall web application security.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/salt-cryptography] Some additional references for using a salt to secure password hashes in specific languages or libraries (PHP, the .NET libraries, etc.) can be found in the external links section below.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] It’s been available across browsers since September 2017.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] The **`SubtleCrypto`** interface of the Web Crypto API provides a number of low-level cryptographic functions.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] The interface name includes the term "subtle" to indicate that many of its algorithms have subtle usage requirements, and hence that it must be used carefully in order to provide suitable security guarantees.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] An instance of `SubtleCrypto` is available as the `subtle` property of the `Crypto` interface, which in turn is available in windows through the `Window.crypto` property and in workers through the `WorkerGlobalScope.crypto` property.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Even assuming you use the basic cryptographic functions correctly, secure key management and overall security system design are extremely hard to get right, and are generally the domain of specialist security experts.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Errors in security system design and implementation can make the security of the system completely ineffective.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Please learn and experiment, but don't guarantee or imply the security of your work before an individual knowledgeable in this subject matter thoroughly reviews it.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] The Crypto 101 Course can be a great place to start learning about the design and implementation of secure systems.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with the encrypted data corresponding to the clear text, algorithm, and key given as parameters.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with the clear data corresponding to the encrypted text, algorithm, and key given as parameters.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with the signature corresponding to the text, algorithm, and key given as parameters.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a boolean value indicating if the signature given as a parameter matches the text, algorithm, and key that are also given as parameters.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a digest generated from the algorithm and text given as parameters.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a newly-generated `CryptoKey`, for symmetrical algorithms, or a `CryptoKeyPair`, containing two newly generated keys, for asymmetrical algorithms.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] These will match the algorithm, usages, and extractability given as parameters.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a newly generated `CryptoKey` derived from the master key and specific algorithm given as parameters.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a newly generated buffer of pseudo-random bits derived from the master key and specific algorithm given as parameters.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a `CryptoKey` corresponding to the format, the algorithm, raw key data, usages, and extractability given as parameters.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with the raw key data containing the key in the requested format.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a wrapped symmetric key for usage (transfer and storage) in insecure environments.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] The wrapped key matches the format specified in the given parameters, and wrapping is done by the given wrapping key, using the specified algorithm.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a `CryptoKey` corresponding to the wrapped key given in the parameter.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] We can split the functions implemented by this API into two groups: cryptography functions and key management functions.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] These are the functions you can use to implement security features such as privacy and authentication in a system.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Except for `digest()`, all the cryptography functions in the API use cryptographic keys.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] In the `SubtleCrypto` API a cryptographic key is represented using a `CryptoKey` object.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] To perform operations like signing and encrypting, you pass a `CryptoKey` object into the `sign()` or `encrypt()` function.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] The `generateKey()` and `deriveKey()` functions both create a new `CryptoKey` object.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] The difference is that `generateKey()` will generate a new distinct key value each time you call it, while `deriveKey()` derives a key from some initial keying material.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] If you provide the same keying material to two separate calls to `deriveKey()`, you will get two `CryptoKey` objects that have the same underlying value.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] This is useful if, for example, you want to derive an encryption key from a password and later derive the same key from the same password to decrypt the data.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] To make keys available outside your app, you need to export the key, and that's what `exportKey()` is for.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] You can choose one of a number of export formats.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] The inverse of `exportKey()` is `importKey()`.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] You can import keys from other systems, and support for standard formats like PKCS #8 and JSON Web Key helps you do this.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] The `exportKey()` function exports the key in an unencrypted format.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] If the key is sensitive you should use `wrapKey()`, which exports the key and then encrypts it using another key; the API calls a "key-wrapping key".
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] The inverse of `wrapKey()` is `unwrapKey()`, which decrypts then imports the key.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] `CryptoKey` is a serializable object, which allows keys to be stored and retrieved using standard web storage APIs.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] The specification expects that most developers will use the IndexedDB API, storing `CryptoKey` objects against some key string identifier that is meaningful to the application, along with any other metadata it finds useful.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] This allows the storage and retrieval of the `CryptoKey` without having to expose its underlying key material to the application or the JavaScript environment.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] The cryptographic functions provided by the Web Crypto API can be performed by one or more different *cryptographic algorithms*: the `algorithm` argument to the function indicates which algorithm to use.
[src:bcrypt-hashing/subtlecrypto] Some algorithms need extra parameters: in these cases the `algorithm` argument is a dictionary object that includes the extra parameters.
